1
00:00:03,837 --> 00:00:05,238
<i>Hello?</i>

2
00:00:05,972 --> 00:00:07,741
<i>Is that… Ogawa?</i>

3
00:00:08,908 --> 00:00:10,877
<i>Hello?</i>

4
00:00:11,444 --> 00:00:12,979
<i>Hello?</i>

5
00:00:13,546 --> 00:00:14,914
Hello,

6
00:00:15,482 --> 00:00:17,017
Kiyoshi's mother!

7
00:00:17,650 --> 00:00:18,585
Can you hear me?

8
00:00:18,651 --> 00:00:20,553
<i>Yes. I can hear you.</i>

9
00:00:21,521 --> 00:00:23,123
This is so frustrating.

10
00:00:23,189 --> 00:00:24,958
Sorry about this.

11
00:00:25,025 --> 00:00:27,093
There's no Wi-Fi here, you see.

12
00:00:27,160 --> 00:00:30,864
But I tried calling using my Pocket WiFi
while standing on a stepladder,

13
00:00:30,930 --> 00:00:33,400
and now I can hear you.

14
00:00:33,466 --> 00:00:34,968
Oh, it's her!

15
00:00:35,935 --> 00:00:36,836
It's her!

16
00:00:36,903 --> 00:00:37,771
Look.

17
00:00:38,872 --> 00:00:40,940
She's Sakae Sakisaka, a feminist.

18
00:00:43,276 --> 00:00:44,844
So she was from over here.

19
00:00:47,547 --> 00:00:50,016
You're famous. Cool.

20
00:00:50,083 --> 00:00:51,217
You put men to shame.

21
00:00:51,785 --> 00:00:55,088
<i>That expression is discriminatory.
It assumes women are inferior.</i>

22
00:00:55,155 --> 00:00:56,156
Whatever.

23
00:00:56,222 --> 00:00:58,458
Mrs. Sakisaka, where are you right now?

24
00:00:58,525 --> 00:00:59,726
<i>Now?</i>

25
00:01:02,362 --> 00:01:04,464
<i>I'm in front of a cafe called Scandal.</i>

26
00:01:04,531 --> 00:01:05,732
What?

27
00:01:07,200 --> 00:01:10,336
Try entering the cafe.

28
00:01:18,044 --> 00:01:19,412
<i>I'm in.</i>

29
00:01:19,479 --> 00:01:20,346
See?

30
00:01:21,147 --> 00:01:22,315
She's in the Showa era.

31
00:01:25,351 --> 00:01:28,488
That means
you really are in the Reiwa era.

32
00:01:28,555 --> 00:01:29,689
Hello.

33
00:01:30,190 --> 00:01:31,491
<i>Are you by yourself?</i>

34
00:01:31,558 --> 00:01:32,725
<i>Take any seat you like.</i>

35
00:01:33,226 --> 00:01:35,128
Huh? Barkeep?

36
00:01:35,195 --> 00:01:37,497
-That's the barkeep?!
-That's him 38 years ago.

37
00:01:37,564 --> 00:01:40,266
Anyway, it's great my call went through.

38
00:01:42,735 --> 00:01:44,137
It's not great at all!

39
00:01:44,204 --> 00:01:47,140
Sorry for the trouble,
but could you go to my house now?

40
00:01:47,207 --> 00:01:48,241
I'll share my address.

41
00:01:48,308 --> 00:01:49,776
What? Why?

42
00:01:49,843 --> 00:01:52,345
My daughter is going
to have rumpy-pumpy with your son!

43
00:01:52,412 --> 00:01:53,513
<i>Rumpy-pumpy?</i>

44
00:01:53,580 --> 00:01:56,950
For some reason, the video of my daughter
when she was little is here,

45
00:01:57,016 --> 00:02:01,654
<i>which means the porn video I confiscated
from a student is inside the VCR.</i>

46
00:02:01,721 --> 00:02:03,056
It's of a lady teacher.

47
00:02:03,123 --> 00:02:06,960
If they watch it, your horny ape of a son
will become even more like an ape!

48
00:02:07,894 --> 00:02:08,862
Kiyoshi.

49
00:02:09,696 --> 00:02:11,164
Kiyoshi.

50
00:02:12,332 --> 00:02:19,038
Kiyoshi!

51
00:02:29,082 --> 00:02:30,250
Who are you?

52
00:02:30,316 --> 00:02:31,518
Step aside!

53
00:02:31,584 --> 00:02:34,220
Kiyoshi!

54
00:02:34,287 --> 00:02:35,822
Are you his mother?

55
00:02:35,889 --> 00:02:37,357
Kiyoshi!

56
00:02:37,857 --> 00:02:38,892
Kiyo…

57
00:02:41,928 --> 00:02:44,297
It seems he lost confidence
after watching this.

58
00:02:44,964 --> 00:02:46,733
All I wanted to see were boobs.

59
00:02:47,867 --> 00:02:50,870
Watching something like that
would make me go insane.

60
00:02:51,704 --> 00:02:53,873
I'm going to go insane.

61
00:02:54,707 --> 00:02:57,510
Where's my stupid geezer?
Why isn't he coming home?

62
00:02:57,577 --> 00:03:00,513
After my baseball club activities,
I boarded a bus.

63
00:03:00,580 --> 00:03:04,150
<i>Then a high school girl wearing
a very short skirt boarded the bus.</i>

64
00:03:05,151 --> 00:03:06,653
-Are these what you saw?
-Yeah.

65
00:03:06,719 --> 00:03:08,922
They're earphones
that transmit sound via Bluetooth.

66
00:03:08,988 --> 00:03:11,858
Transmit sound? Via Bluetooth?

67
00:03:11,925 --> 00:03:14,327
And what happened
when you stepped off the bus?

68
00:03:14,394 --> 00:03:16,362
A package of hi-lite was 520 yen.

69
00:03:16,429 --> 00:03:17,597
<i>I met you.</i>

70
00:03:17,664 --> 00:03:20,333
<i>I went to the toilet and saw
Kyon Kyon's 40th anniversary poster.</i>

71
00:03:20,400 --> 00:03:23,970
<i>There was a hole in the wall
that led to the Showa era.</i>

72
00:03:25,238 --> 00:03:27,106
You arrived here from the past by bus,

73
00:03:27,173 --> 00:03:29,475
and you returned to the past
through the toilet?

74
00:03:29,542 --> 00:03:31,811
So the toilet is a gateway
to the Showa era.

75
00:03:31,878 --> 00:03:34,214
Until the other day. But not anymore.

76
00:03:35,415 --> 00:03:36,449
I can't go back.

77
00:03:36,516 --> 00:03:37,917
Because you renovated it!

78
00:03:37,984 --> 00:03:40,887
I mean, it's outdated
to have a Japanese-style toilet.

79
00:03:41,888 --> 00:03:43,790
I'm sorry, I guess.

80
00:03:43,856 --> 00:03:45,525
I'm the one to blame?

81
00:03:45,592 --> 00:03:46,960
Why did you come back?

82
00:03:47,527 --> 00:03:50,029
Huh? Well…

83
00:03:50,096 --> 00:03:51,631
Because…

84
00:03:52,465 --> 00:03:54,234
Did you forget something here?

85
00:03:54,968 --> 00:03:56,269
Because, um…

86
00:03:58,238 --> 00:04:00,473
I was curious about you.

87
00:04:02,809 --> 00:04:03,776
Me?

88
00:04:03,843 --> 00:04:04,944
Yeah, you.

89
00:04:05,445 --> 00:04:06,813
You were crying the other day.

90
00:04:06,879 --> 00:04:08,781
My baby finally fell asleep.

91
00:04:09,749 --> 00:04:14,254
If you'd like,
I can lend you a listening ear.

92
00:04:21,060 --> 00:04:23,162
Sorry. I accidentally paired
the earphones.

93
00:04:23,229 --> 00:04:24,497
Paired?

94
00:04:26,699 --> 00:04:30,770
<i>Your daughter… having rumpy-pumpy.</i>

95
00:04:30,837 --> 00:04:31,904
What?

96
00:04:31,971 --> 00:04:33,873
I managed to prevent them.

97
00:04:33,940 --> 00:04:37,644
Also, it seems I can connect to the Wi-Fi
when in this position.

98
00:04:37,710 --> 00:04:39,245
The stepladder had nothing to do with it.

99
00:04:40,780 --> 00:04:41,914
So, what will you do?

100
00:04:42,515 --> 00:04:44,450
Do you know how you can come back?

101
00:04:44,517 --> 00:04:45,885
I don't.

102
00:04:45,952 --> 00:04:47,186
Do you?

103
00:04:47,253 --> 00:04:48,855
What's with that bus anyway?

104
00:04:48,921 --> 00:04:51,658
This is a real pain.
There's a baseball match tomorrow!

105
00:04:51,724 --> 00:04:53,393
<i>What are you doing?!</i>

106
00:04:56,829 --> 00:04:59,365
What's wrong with high school girls
in the Showa era?

107
00:04:59,432 --> 00:05:01,968
As soon as you look away,
they start going at it.

108
00:05:02,035 --> 00:05:04,003
I can't let my guard down at all.

109
00:05:04,070 --> 00:05:07,307
-Shut up, you hysteric biddy!
-What?

110
00:05:07,373 --> 00:05:09,909
Who cares?
It's not like it's the end of the world.

111
00:05:09,976 --> 00:05:11,678
Everyone else has gone through it!

112
00:05:11,744 --> 00:05:14,280
Being a virgin isn't cool these days!

113
00:05:14,347 --> 00:05:18,284
I want to live it up in my teens
and become a Clarion Girl!

114
00:05:18,851 --> 00:05:21,187
This is my business card
from my previous job.

115
00:05:21,888 --> 00:05:24,657
EBS? You worked at a TV station?

116
00:05:24,724 --> 00:05:28,428
I had a passion for comedy
and hoped to work with variety shows,

117
00:05:28,494 --> 00:05:30,630
but I ended up in the news department.

118
00:05:30,697 --> 00:05:32,865
I was sent to the New York branch,

119
00:05:32,932 --> 00:05:35,501
where I met my husband,
who worked as a correspondent.

120
00:05:35,568 --> 00:05:37,437
Ryusuke Taniguchi.

121
00:05:37,503 --> 00:05:40,073
-He's a freelance journalist now.
-Wow.

122
00:05:40,139 --> 00:05:41,941
He's got 1.58 million subscribers!

123
00:05:42,008 --> 00:05:43,710
-What are you talking about?
-Look.

124
00:05:44,711 --> 00:05:47,847
<i>Welcome to Ryusuke Taniguchi's channel,</i>
Sound Arguments.

125
00:05:47,914 --> 00:05:52,385
<i>Today, I will present sound arguments
about environmental issues.</i>

126
00:05:52,452 --> 00:05:54,387
<i>Waste sorting.</i>

127
00:05:56,489 --> 00:05:58,024
<i>Super important.</i>

128
00:05:58,091 --> 00:05:59,125
<i>This is because…</i>

129
00:05:59,192 --> 00:06:03,396
Like that, he basically only presents
sound arguments.

130
00:06:03,463 --> 00:06:05,465
But the night view of New York
was gorgeous,

131
00:06:05,531 --> 00:06:08,434
and it just felt like
he was saying something cool.

132
00:06:09,535 --> 00:06:13,239
And I wanted to show myself
in a wedding dress to my father soon.

133
00:06:14,674 --> 00:06:18,878
My mother passed away in the year
of the Great Hanshin earthquake.

134
00:06:19,812 --> 00:06:21,514
The Great Hanshin earthquake?

135
00:06:21,581 --> 00:06:24,951
When you don't know something,
you just Google it, like this.

136
00:06:25,017 --> 00:06:25,852
See?

137
00:06:25,918 --> 00:06:28,020
What? Are you kidding me?

138
00:06:28,087 --> 00:06:30,323
1995? That's nine years from now.

139
00:06:31,090 --> 00:06:32,158
An earthquake that big?

140
00:06:32,225 --> 00:06:35,762
Another one hit Tohoku in 2011.

141
00:06:35,828 --> 00:06:39,298
Huh, I see. I'll keep that in mind.

142
00:06:41,067 --> 00:06:42,135
And then?

143
00:06:43,202 --> 00:06:46,539
Then I came back to Japan
when I married him.

144
00:06:46,606 --> 00:06:48,941
All your memories are in there, huh?

145
00:06:49,909 --> 00:06:52,145
Huh? Oh, yeah.

146
00:06:52,812 --> 00:06:54,614
Losing it would be a big deal, then.

147
00:06:55,181 --> 00:06:56,182
And?

148
00:06:56,749 --> 00:07:00,253
My husband supported my decision
to continue working.

149
00:07:00,319 --> 00:07:02,221
And I was chosen as the assistant producer

150
00:07:02,288 --> 00:07:04,724
in the variety department
I've been longing to join.

151
00:07:05,324 --> 00:07:08,394
Just as my job was becoming interesting,

152
00:07:09,095 --> 00:07:12,331
I discovered I was pregnant with Masato.

153
00:07:13,099 --> 00:07:17,737
My husband was involved in childcare
and told me not to shoulder everything.

154
00:07:18,604 --> 00:07:23,976
He kept telling me, "If there's anything
I can do, just let me know."

155
00:07:24,043 --> 00:07:25,011
Revolting.

156
00:07:26,012 --> 00:07:27,947
-What?
-No, go on.

157
00:07:29,582 --> 00:07:31,818
I was eager to return to work quickly.

158
00:07:31,884 --> 00:07:34,353
Even while on maternity leave,
I made a project plan

159
00:07:34,420 --> 00:07:36,689
and prepared myself
to rejoin the workforce.

160
00:07:37,590 --> 00:07:41,394
But I didn't pass the screening
to enroll the baby in a nursery.

161
00:07:42,128 --> 00:07:43,830
Even though you both worked?

162
00:07:44,897 --> 00:07:46,699
The person at the ward office said,

163
00:07:46,766 --> 00:07:50,903
"Your husband is
on paternity leave, isn't he?"

164
00:07:50,970 --> 00:07:52,905
<i>I'm going to share a sound argument.</i>

165
00:07:52,972 --> 00:07:54,006
<i>Paternity leave.</i>

166
00:07:55,241 --> 00:07:56,976
<i>You should definitely take it.</i>

167
00:07:57,043 --> 00:07:58,711
<i>I will also take time off work.</i>

168
00:07:59,278 --> 00:08:00,446
<i>The reason is…</i>

169
00:08:00,513 --> 00:08:02,982
His argument is sound, but the timing is…

170
00:08:03,049 --> 00:08:04,550
When I spoke with my supervisor,

171
00:08:04,617 --> 00:08:06,752
the company was promoting
the Work Style Reform.

172
00:08:06,819 --> 00:08:09,989
They were planning to set up
a daycare in their annex next year,

173
00:08:10,056 --> 00:08:13,593
so he urged me to make use of it
and share its benefits with others.

174
00:08:13,659 --> 00:08:15,895
I finally managed to return to the office.

175
00:08:16,562 --> 00:08:17,463
Good morning!

176
00:08:17,530 --> 00:08:19,732
-Good morning.
-You're early.

177
00:08:19,799 --> 00:08:22,001
-Sorry.
-I will open the door right now.

178
00:08:22,602 --> 00:08:24,604
Here we go.

179
00:08:25,471 --> 00:08:27,473
-Here are his diapers and baby wipes.
-Right.

180
00:08:27,540 --> 00:08:29,108
-And this is his baby food.
-Right.

181
00:08:29,175 --> 00:08:31,310
If he refuses to eat,
there's jelly in this bag.

182
00:08:31,377 --> 00:08:32,979
-Here we go, Machato.
-Right.

183
00:08:33,045 --> 00:08:34,914
Be a good boy, okay?

184
00:08:34,981 --> 00:08:36,415
-See you later.
-Take care.

185
00:08:38,718 --> 00:08:42,021
Mr. Uryu, here's the project plan I made
during my maternity leave.

186
00:08:42,588 --> 00:08:45,391
Meet Ai, the new assistant producer.

187
00:08:45,458 --> 00:08:46,726
Please hand over your tasks.

188
00:08:46,792 --> 00:08:49,028
H-Hand over?

189
00:08:49,095 --> 00:08:52,532
You're being promoted to producer,
and I'm stepping into an executive role.

190
00:08:53,599 --> 00:08:56,035
Right, of course.

191
00:08:56,102 --> 00:08:58,571
Let me know if there's anything
I can support you.

192
00:09:01,507 --> 00:09:05,611
You look at the cast lineup for the day
and allocate dressing rooms accordingly.

193
00:09:05,678 --> 00:09:08,314
Put this person in Room D,
close to the smoking area.

194
00:09:08,381 --> 00:09:13,185
This duo hates each other, so assign them
Rooms A and G, situated farthest apart.

195
00:09:13,252 --> 00:09:17,723
Mr. Mushanokoji, the main emcee,
is into feng shui and fortune-telling.

196
00:09:17,790 --> 00:09:20,293
So, I always switch the color
of the curtains to purple.

197
00:09:20,359 --> 00:09:21,294
Got it.

198
00:09:21,360 --> 00:09:23,563
Wait. Aren't you going to take notes?

199
00:09:23,629 --> 00:09:25,998
No, I don't use paper.

200
00:09:26,699 --> 00:09:27,767
I see.

201
00:09:29,535 --> 00:09:30,937
Where are you going?

202
00:09:31,003 --> 00:09:32,638
To say hello to Mr. Mushanokoji.

203
00:09:32,705 --> 00:09:33,973
No!

204
00:09:34,040 --> 00:09:35,708
Never until the show is over.

205
00:09:35,775 --> 00:09:39,078
But Mr. Sakakibara will lecture you
if you don't greet him,

206
00:09:39,145 --> 00:09:40,613
so go do it now!

207
00:09:44,650 --> 00:09:46,052
BABYSITTER

208
00:09:53,159 --> 00:09:54,760
Your mommy is coming, okay?

209
00:09:54,827 --> 00:09:55,861
What's the matter?

210
00:09:55,928 --> 00:09:57,129
I'm so sorry.

211
00:09:57,196 --> 00:10:00,566
I glanced away for a moment, and I think
he may have swallowed a marble.

212
00:10:01,067 --> 00:10:01,901
You think?

213
00:10:01,968 --> 00:10:04,270
When I counted them, one was missing.

214
00:10:06,539 --> 00:10:09,909
Machato, did you swallow a marble?

215
00:10:09,976 --> 00:10:11,143
Machato?

216
00:10:12,712 --> 00:10:14,947
-Hello?
-<i>Hello?</i>

217
00:10:15,014 --> 00:10:19,652
<i>I tasked Ai with booking plane tickets
for the overseas location shoot.</i>

218
00:10:19,719 --> 00:10:20,953
<i>Could you check on her?</i>

219
00:10:21,020 --> 00:10:22,688
Economy seats will do for them.

220
00:10:22,755 --> 00:10:26,859
These young people here
should be fine with economy seats.

221
00:10:26,926 --> 00:10:30,429
But Mr. Ikusaburo Yamazaki
is flying business class.

222
00:10:30,496 --> 00:10:33,199
Won't the others with longer careers
see it as unfair?

223
00:10:33,833 --> 00:10:35,668
Then, arrange separate flights for them.

224
00:10:35,735 --> 00:10:36,802
I see.

225
00:10:36,869 --> 00:10:38,104
-May I?
-Sure.

226
00:10:39,839 --> 00:10:42,575
They won't know
unless they are on the same flight.

227
00:10:43,142 --> 00:10:46,012
"If I'm flying economy,
they must be flying economy, too."

228
00:10:46,078 --> 00:10:49,315
"If I'm flying business,
they must be flying economy."

229
00:10:49,382 --> 00:10:51,584
That's how celebrities tend to think.

230
00:10:51,651 --> 00:10:53,019
That's good to know.

231
00:10:53,085 --> 00:10:55,721
And having a standard makes it easier.

232
00:10:55,788 --> 00:10:58,724
In my case,
I use Norito Yashima as the benchmark.

233
00:10:58,791 --> 00:11:01,460
-Mr. Yashima? The one with glasses?
-Yeah, him.

234
00:11:01,527 --> 00:11:04,930
Doesn't he seem like the type
who won't complain about an economy seat?

235
00:11:05,931 --> 00:11:08,034
But he would appreciate
a business class seat.

236
00:11:08,100 --> 00:11:08,934
True.

237
00:11:09,835 --> 00:11:12,805
When in doubt, I consider
whether they're above or below Yashima.

238
00:11:12,872 --> 00:11:14,407
-Your phone is ringing.
-Right.

239
00:11:14,473 --> 00:11:15,841
-Good luck.
-Good luck.

240
00:11:15,908 --> 00:11:17,376
-Can I look at the script?
-Sure.

241
00:11:20,646 --> 00:11:21,981
-Here you go.
-Thanks.

242
00:11:26,018 --> 00:11:27,987
Place the bento boxes
in the dressing rooms,

243
00:11:28,054 --> 00:11:30,322
then copy the second script
and allocate the rooms.

244
00:11:30,389 --> 00:11:32,291
Um, I'm clocking out for the day.

245
00:11:32,358 --> 00:11:34,393
What? But we're shooting
two programs today.

246
00:11:34,460 --> 00:11:37,029
-Sorry, but my shift is over.
-What are you doing, Ai?

247
00:11:37,096 --> 00:11:38,531
Your shift is over.

248
00:11:38,597 --> 00:11:40,433
-Head home already!
-Right. Sorry.

249
00:11:40,499 --> 00:11:43,102
This is Elza.
She's taking over for the afternoon shift.

250
00:11:43,169 --> 00:11:45,071
Please hand over your tasks.

251
00:11:46,806 --> 00:11:48,507
